{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17588536","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17588536"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T09:10:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T09:10:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15168"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15168","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15168"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7859"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66462"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7859"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15168"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51913"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2058"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19158"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19161"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22221"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66462"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EOral leukoplakia is a well recognised clinical condition, being found in about 1% of the population (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Most lesions represent epithelial hypertrophy","Dysplastic changes are present in up to 20% of cases","Biopsy is only indicated if symptoms are present","Spontaneous resolution occurs in most cases","Treatment with topical antifungals is indicated"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EOral leukoplakia is defined as a predominantly white lesion of the oral mucosa that cannot be characterised clinically or pathologically as any other disease. It is considered a potentially malignant disorder, with significant risk for malignant transformation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDysplastic changes are present in up to 20% of cases\u003C/strong\u003E, which is why all persistent leukoplakic lesions should be biopsied to rule out dysplasia or malignancy. The risk of malignant transformation is particularly high for lesions on the lateral tongue and floor of mouth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMost lesions represent epithelial hypertrophy\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While hyperkeratosis is often present, the histological appearance can vary significantly and may include dysplasia, hyperplasia, or even carcinoma in situ.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBiopsy is only indicated if symptoms are present\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. All persistent leukoplakic lesions should be biopsied regardless of symptoms, as many premalignant and early malignant lesions are asymptomatic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpontaneous resolution occurs in most cases\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While some lesions may resolve with removal of risk factors (such as smoking cessation), many persist and require ongoing monitoring or intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETreatment with topical antifungals\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Unlike candidiasis, leukoplakia cannot be scraped off and does not respond to antifungal treatment. The mainstay of management includes risk factor modification and regular surveillance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Oral leukoplakia is a white patch that cannot be characterised clinically or pathologically as any other disease.","Up to 20% of oral leukoplakia cases show dysplastic changes on biopsy.","Tobacco use is the most significant risk factor for oral leukoplakia."],"references":["Mohammed F, Fairozekhan AT. Oral Leukoplakia. [Updated 2023 Jul 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK442013/","Dilhari A, Weerasekera MM, Siriwardhana A, Maheshika O, Gunasekara C, Karunathilaka S, Nagahawatte A, Fernando N. Candida infection in oral leukoplakia: an unperceived public health problem. Acta Odontol Scand. 2016 Oct;74(7):565-569. doi: 10.1080/00016357.2016.1220018. Epub 2016 Aug 19. PMID: 27538681","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51913"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15168"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21267"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21267"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/XHpoWA1pQGH27dqrPDy3dvudwPMLTV.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/XHpoWA1pQGH27dqrPDy3dvudwPMLTV.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":324,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51913","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51913"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-30T11:58:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-30T11:58:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7859"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66462"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji"